<p>In the latest development, Iran’s judiciary signaled fast-track trials and possible executions for people detained in nationwide protests, as authorities continue a severe crackdown and restrict communications through a major internet blackout. President Trump publicly warned the United States would take “very strong action” if Iran begins hanging protesters, while also urging Iranians to keep protesting and saying unspecified “help is on the way”. Rights groups and Western officials cited by multiple outlets say the death toll has risen into the thousands, though exact figures remain disputed amid limited access and conflicting reporting. The standoff is drawing wider diplomatic attention as some European governments moved to formally protest Iran’s handling of the unrest.</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/qKidCHPthqLzH026zA25Ui2chcMUq9oYQGlCNBki9wTNz8lA5I8-rwcTQd9vXChoo6WaMmlQpBE_sD1OrXBKBACIdcpq6ZYY3VR5VnKgVRhttUpZu84Yam8VrAhYWisKIbbxzQ5AXX-LPD-99Lnn-VkPCuRds1y_l1MxNZMJu4kptFIrRwSHJER51eq5u8P-60Q' alt='A burned-out building in Tehran amid the most expansive protests in years.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Why protests: Reports describe the unrest as being triggered by economic pressures including soaring prices, inflation, and a plunging currency, with some coverage pointing to currency collapse as an early spark.</li><li>Diplomacy paused: President Trump said he canceled meetings with Iranian officials until the killing stops, and one report said he also canceled meetings on Tuesday.</li><li>Capital charges: Iranian prosecutors said some suspects could face the capital charge of “moharebeh” (“waging war against God”) in connection with the demonstrations.</li><li>Communications squeeze: After days of broad disruption, some reports said international phone links briefly allowed outgoing mobile calls, but people still could not reliably receive calls and texting/internet access remained heavily restricted.</li><li>Strike planning: The White House was reported to be reviewing military strike options as advisers met, with some political allies warning about the risk of a wider war.</li></ul><blockquote>We will take very strong action if they do such a thing - President Donald Trump</blockquote><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>President Trump / US government: President Trump says Iranians should keep protesting and that the US will respond strongly if executions begin, while not detailing what “help” would include. (<a href='https://www.nytimes.com/2026/01/13/world/middleeast/trump-iran-antigovernment-protests.html'>The New York Times</a>)</li><li>Iranian judiciary: Iran’s judiciary chief signaled rapid trials and executions for detained protesters, indicating a hard-line legal response to the unrest. (<a href='https://www.scmp.com/news/world/middle-east/article/3339852/iran-signals-fast-trials-and-executions-detained-protesters-after-trump-warning'>South China Morning Post</a>)</li><li>Iran’s UN mission / Iranian officials: Iran rejected US warnings as part of a regime-change “playbook,” arguing Washington seeks to manufacture a pretext for intervention. (<a href='https://www.dawn.com/news/1966899/trump-warns-of-very-strong-action-if-iran-hangs-protesters'>Dawn</a>)</li><li>Gulf US allies (regional view): Some Gulf partners fear US involvement could produce destabilizing, “catastrophic” regional consequences, even if it fails to remove Iran’s leadership. (<a href='https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/politics/article/3339819/trump-vs-iran-gulf-allies-fear-us-help-may-unleash-chaos'>South China Morning Post</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.bbc.com/news/videos/c4g0d892p7go'>Trump vows &#x27;very strong action&#x27; if Iran executes protesters</a> - bbc.com</li><li><a href='https://www.semafor.com/article/01/13/2026/trump-pledges-help-for-iran-protesters'>Trump pledges ‘help’ for Iran protesters</a> - semafor.com</li><li><a href='https://www.pbs.org/newshour/show/as-iran-protesters-face-ruthless-c